An Object in JavaScript is a collection of key-value pairs used to store related data and functionality together.
Think of an object as a real-world entity. For example, a student has properties like name, age, and grade. Instead of storing these values in separate variables, we can store them in a single object.

Objects store data as key-value pairs.
Properties hold values.
Methods are functions inside objects.
Use dot notation or bracket notation to access properties.
Properties can be added, updated, or deleted dynamically.
this refers to the current object.
